SIMPLE: proctor
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proctor
<hw>Proc"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>proketour</ets>, contr. fr. <ets>procurator</ets>. See
<er>Procurator</er>.]</ety> <def>One who is employed to manage to
affairs of another.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A person
appointed to collect alms for those who could not go out to beg for
themselves, as lepers, the bedridden, etc.; hence a beggar.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Nares.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>
<def>An officer employed in admiralty and ecclesiastical causes. He
answers to an <xex>attorney</xex> at common law, or to a
<xex>solicitor</xex> in equity.</def> <au>Wharton.</au> <sd>(c)</sd>
<fld>(Ch. of Eng.)</fld> <def>A representative of the clergy in
convocation.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>An officer in a university or
college whose duty it is to enforce obedience to the laws of the
institution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- hall proctor. a proctor(d) who maintains order within the
hallways of a school, esp. during a shange of class. THe post is often
occupied by a student -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proctor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Proctor
<hw>Proc"tor</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To act as a proctor toward; to
manage as an attorney or agent.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Warburton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proctorage</ent>⟦br⟧
